It's one of the primary--our
need for energy is one of the

00:00:09.067 --> 00:00:14.967
primary ways that we interact
with the environment, both

00:00:14.967 --> 00:00:18.433
draw resources from it,
but also influence the

00:00:18.433 --> 00:00:19.067
environment.

00:00:19.067 --> 00:00:25.700
So I think it's a fitting way
to end up the course.

00:00:25.700 --> 00:00:28.200
Today I'll probably just
get through these two.

00:00:28.200 --> 00:00:30.800
Although, so I've put hydropower
down here and

00:00:30.800 --> 00:00:32.967
renewable for the future.

00:00:32.967 --> 00:00:34.733
But it's a big player today.

00:00:34.733 --> 00:00:38.067
So I'll probably talk about
hydropower today.

00:00:38.067 --> 00:00:44.100
But the rest will be discussed
mostly on Wednesday.

00:00:44.100 --> 00:00:49.933
Now, over here, then, is the
cartoon that will kind of

00:00:49.933 --> 00:00:52.300
remind us where everything
fits in this

00:00:52.300 --> 00:00:57.867
picture of energy resources.

00:00:57.867 --> 00:01:03.400
Hydroelectric comes from rain
falling on high ground, so it

00:01:03.400 --> 00:01:04.633
has potential energy.

00:01:04.633 --> 00:01:07.767
If it falls at sea level,
you can't get any

00:01:07.767 --> 00:01:08.867
hydro energy from it.

00:01:08.867 --> 00:01:11.833
But if it falls at a high
altitude, you've got that

00:01:11.833 --> 00:01:15.167
potential energy to draw from.

00:01:15.167 --> 00:01:19.233
The sun, through photosynthesis,
will allow

00:01:19.233 --> 00:01:20.100
plants to grow.

00:01:20.100 --> 00:01:22.633
And then you can use
that biomass in

00:01:22.633 --> 00:01:24.933
several different ways.

00:01:24.933 --> 00:01:31.067
Direct conversion of solar
to, say, electricity.

00:01:31.067 --> 00:01:35.000
The differential heating from
the sun, as you know, can

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:36.933
create the winds.

00:01:36.933 --> 00:01:40.967
And the winds can turn
a wind turbine.

00:01:40.967 --> 00:01:44.500
The winds also produce
waves on the ocean.

00:01:44.500 --> 00:01:51.500
And those waves can be used
to generate electricity.

00:01:51.500 --> 00:01:57.867
The heat from the sun also
creates a temperature

00:01:57.867 --> 00:02:00.133
difference within the oceans.

00:02:00.133 --> 00:02:03.767
If the thermocline is there,
you've got warm water above

00:02:03.767 --> 00:02:04.900
and cold water below.

00:02:04.900 --> 00:02:08.100
And that temperature difference
can be used to

00:02:08.100 --> 00:02:11.500
derive a kind of renewable
energy.

00:02:15.267 --> 00:02:19.133
The moon and the sun, their
gravitational pull on the

00:02:19.133 --> 00:02:22.867
earth, produce tides.

00:02:22.867 --> 00:02:26.300
And that can be tapped
for energy.

00:02:26.300 --> 00:02:29.067
Everything else comes
from down within the

00:02:29.067 --> 00:02:31.800
interior of the earth.

00:02:31.800 --> 00:02:37.067
Oil and gas in the ocean bottom
comes mostly from algae

00:02:37.067 --> 00:02:41.200
that grew, or phytoplankton
that grew in the ocean

00:02:41.200 --> 00:02:43.900
millions of years ago and then
fell to the bottom and got

00:02:43.900 --> 00:02:45.133
covered over.

00:02:47.500 --> 00:02:53.900
Coal, oil, and natural gas on
the continents came from

00:02:53.900 --> 00:02:57.467
ancient biomass that
got covered over.

00:03:00.267 --> 00:03:03.867
Geothermal comes from the fact
that the interior of

00:03:03.867 --> 00:03:06.567
the earth is hot.

00:03:06.567 --> 00:03:10.400
And sometimes those hot rocks or
hot lava can come up pretty

00:03:10.400 --> 00:03:12.133
close to the surface.

00:03:12.133 --> 00:03:15.533
And then that temperature
gradient can be used for

00:03:15.533 --> 00:03:16.600
renewable energy.

00:03:16.600 --> 00:03:22.433
There is also uranium in the
crust. In fact, some of this

00:03:22.433 --> 00:03:26.433
geothermal heat comes from the
natural decay of uranium.

00:03:26.433 --> 00:03:29.600
But we can also dig up that
uranium and use it in a

00:03:29.600 --> 00:03:33.533
nuclear power plant.

00:03:33.533 --> 00:03:34.967
What have I left out?

00:03:34.967 --> 00:03:37.833
Is there anything, any
renewables you can think of

00:03:37.833 --> 00:03:40.533
that I don't have on there,
or any form of energy not

00:03:40.533 --> 00:03:41.767
included there?

00:03:45.667 --> 00:03:47.600
OK, let's start to go
through this then.

00:03:52.233 --> 00:03:56.400
So first of all, we have to
remind ourselves about units.

00:03:56.400 --> 00:03:58.900
You guys are good at this by
now, so I won't spend much

00:03:58.900 --> 00:03:59.500
time on it.

00:03:59.500 --> 00:04:06.400
But the SI system of unit
of energy is the Joule.

00:04:06.400 --> 00:04:09.400
The unit of powers
is the watt.

00:04:09.400 --> 00:04:17.033
Energy is power times the time
over which you are using it.

00:04:17.033 --> 00:04:21.333
So a watt second is a Joule.

00:04:21.333 --> 00:04:25.900
And inversely, power is
energy per unit time.

00:04:25.900 --> 00:04:29.133
So a Joule per second
is a watt.

00:04:31.700 --> 00:04:35.100
However, when we're talking
about electricity, there is a

00:04:35.100 --> 00:04:40.600
non-SI unit that is
quite standard.

00:04:40.600 --> 00:04:42.400
And that's the kilowatt hour.

00:04:45.100 --> 00:04:47.500
So the watt is an SI
system of unit.

00:04:47.500 --> 00:04:51.167
And we're used to putting
a prefix on it

00:04:51.167 --> 00:04:52.367
kilo meeting 1,000.

00:04:52.367 --> 00:04:55.600
But then the time unit is an
hour instead of a second.

00:04:55.600 --> 00:05:00.767
So that kind of messes up the
SI system a little bit.

00:05:00.767 --> 00:05:04.667
But it's easy to go back and
forth, because as you know,

00:05:04.667 --> 00:05:11.967
there are 3,600 seconds in
an hour, 60 times 60.

00:05:11.967 --> 00:05:18.300
And therefore, one kilowatt
hour is 3.6 megaJoules.

00:05:18.300 --> 00:05:20.700
And you don't have
to memorize that.

00:05:20.700 --> 00:05:24.000
Just remember how many seconds
there are in an hour.

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:28.433
You can just work that out, that
correspondence, anytime

00:05:28.433 --> 00:05:30.900
you need it.

00:05:30.900 --> 00:05:35.900
But it's odd, because
it's an energy unit.

00:05:35.900 --> 00:05:40.367
It has a power times a time.

00:05:40.367 --> 00:05:43.100
So it's a little like this,
except we end up not with

00:05:43.100 --> 00:05:46.267
Joules, but kilowatt hours.

00:05:46.267 --> 00:05:48.733
And if you're an economist and
you want to have something to

00:05:48.733 --> 00:05:53.167
remember about this unit
kilowatt hour, well, it's

00:05:53.167 --> 00:05:55.900
about $0.10 per kilowatt
hour when I pay my

00:05:55.900 --> 00:05:58.933
electric bill at home.

00:05:58.933 --> 00:06:02.067
It varies by a factor of two
or three across the country

00:06:02.067 --> 00:06:05.767
however, so that's not
a fixed value.

00:06:05.767 --> 00:06:07.000
Any questions there?

00:06:09.567 --> 00:06:14.767
Now, it is convenient to break
up our use of energy into

00:06:14.767 --> 00:06:18.500
three general categories.

00:06:18.500 --> 00:06:22.667
I think you'll appreciate this
as we go through the material.

00:06:22.667 --> 00:06:25.100
Although it seems a little bit
odd in the beginning to break

00:06:25.100 --> 00:06:26.867
it up in this particular way.

00:06:26.867 --> 00:06:29.700
We use energy for heating,
heating your home, for

00:06:29.700 --> 00:06:32.833
example, just to raise
the temperature.

00:06:32.833 --> 00:06:36.900
It's a very kind of low-tech
way of using energy.

00:06:36.900 --> 00:06:41.167
In fact, it's the lowest form
of energy when you're just

00:06:41.167 --> 00:06:44.100
using heat to raise the
temperature of something.

00:06:44.100 --> 00:06:48.667
Transportation, moving
goods or people.

00:06:48.667 --> 00:06:53.533
You can use gas in your car
for that, or diesel fuel.

00:06:53.533 --> 00:07:00.367
And then electricity, which
is a very broad category.

00:07:00.367 --> 00:07:06.467
It includes electric motors,
lighting, electronics.

00:07:06.467 --> 00:07:09.400
But you can also use electronics
for heating and

00:07:09.400 --> 00:07:11.400
for transportation.

00:07:11.400 --> 00:07:14.800
So electricity is a very
broad category.

00:07:14.800 --> 00:07:18.333
But it's a much higher form of
energy in a sense that I'll be

00:07:18.333 --> 00:07:24.167
describing later than just
raising the temperature by

00:07:24.167 --> 00:07:26.500
adding heat.

00:07:26.500 --> 00:07:30.800
So we'll see how well that
three-part categorization

00:07:30.800 --> 00:07:32.867
works for us as we go through.

00:07:32.867 --> 00:07:36.300
And then, of course, there's
all these energy resources.

00:07:36.300 --> 00:07:39.567
These are the ones that I put
on the cartoon over there.

00:07:39.567 --> 00:07:42.367
I'll just run over them briefly
here and make a few

00:07:42.367 --> 00:07:44.267
additional comments.

00:07:44.267 --> 00:07:47.500
And we'll be going through most
of these in some detail

00:07:47.500 --> 00:07:49.600
today and tomorrow.

00:07:49.600 --> 00:07:50.600
Coal.

00:07:50.600 --> 00:07:52.633
There's lots of it.

00:07:52.633 --> 00:07:56.600
It is rather heavily polluting,
puts a lot of CO2

00:07:56.600 --> 00:07:59.533
in the atmosphere
by burning coal,

00:07:59.533 --> 00:08:02.500
oxidizing it to form CO2.

00:08:02.500 --> 00:08:04.367
Oil and natural gas.

00:08:04.367 --> 00:08:07.367
There's less of it than coal.

00:08:07.367 --> 00:08:10.633
It's less polluting, both
in terms of local air

00:08:10.633 --> 00:08:17.367
pollution--that is to say, less
sulfur, less mercury,

00:08:17.367 --> 00:08:27.567
generally less ash also, it's
at about 20% less CO2

00:08:27.567 --> 00:08:33.200
emissions per Joule of
energy than is coal.

00:08:33.200 --> 00:08:39.600
So it's better in almost every
respect than coal, except

00:08:39.600 --> 00:08:40.667
there's less of it.

00:08:40.667 --> 00:08:46.467
Nuclear plentiful, mostly
non-polluting.

00:08:46.467 --> 00:08:49.600
Certainly, it puts no CO2
in the atmosphere.

00:08:49.600 --> 00:08:53.833
Waste storage is a problem, and
public resistance because

00:08:53.833 --> 00:09:00.133
of a danger factor with
nuclear plants.

00:09:00.133 --> 00:09:05.700
Hydroelectric falls into
the renewable category.

00:09:05.700 --> 00:09:09.433
Clean, it's limited, and you
lose natural rivers and

00:09:09.433 --> 00:09:15.033
ecosystems when you dam up large
valley systems. There is

00:09:15.033 --> 00:09:19.000
a technology, though, called
run-of-the-river

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:22.033
hydroelectric, where
you don't dam it.

00:09:22.033 --> 00:09:27.367
You just take the flow that's
there on any particular day to

00:09:27.367 --> 00:09:29.133
put through your hydroelectric
plant.

00:09:29.133 --> 00:09:32.667
That avoids the big dam, the
big reservoir, and avoids a

00:09:32.667 --> 00:09:36.467
lot of the loss of natural
rivers and ecosystems. So you

00:09:36.467 --> 00:09:41.267
can do hydroelectric
without damming up.

00:09:41.267 --> 00:09:43.867
But it's not usually done.

00:09:43.867 --> 00:09:47.633
Wind is renewable, moderate
cost. A lot of people don't

00:09:47.633 --> 00:09:51.367
like to look at windmills.

00:09:51.367 --> 00:09:53.367
So there's public resistance
to it.

00:09:53.367 --> 00:09:56.367
Also, sometimes there
can be noise and

00:09:56.367 --> 00:10:01.167
issues about bird kill.

00:10:01.167 --> 00:10:05.667
Solar renewable, high cost.
Also, some people don't like

00:10:05.667 --> 00:10:10.567
to see the landscape covered
with solar panels.

00:10:10.567 --> 00:10:13.200
Ocean waves and tides haven't
made very much progress.

00:10:13.200 --> 00:10:13.833
It's renewable.

00:10:13.833 --> 00:10:17.600
It's very high cost to build
something that's going to sit

00:10:17.600 --> 00:10:21.133
in the ocean and move around
and draw energy from

00:10:21.133 --> 00:10:22.000
the waves and tides.

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:24.700
The engineering really
isn't there yet.

00:10:24.700 --> 00:10:26.333
And biomass.

00:10:26.333 --> 00:10:32.467
Renewable, polluting if you
burn it, but no net CO2

00:10:32.467 --> 00:10:35.700
because you're drawing in CO2
from the atmosphere to make

00:10:35.700 --> 00:10:37.800
the biomass.

00:10:37.800 --> 00:10:40.400
And then when you burn it,
you put the CO2 back.

00:10:40.400 --> 00:10:43.767
If you're only putting the CO2
back, it wouldn't be too bad.

00:10:43.767 --> 00:10:51.433
But you're also putting in ash,
probably some mercury,

00:10:51.433 --> 00:10:56.667
other things along with that
burning of the biomass.

00:10:56.667 --> 00:10:58.800
Any questions there?

00:10:58.800 --> 00:10:59.100
All right.

